3.14	We recommended to the management to:
Require the accountable officers granted with cash advance to liquidate within the prescribed period in accordance with Section 1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 to ensure the timely recognition of expenses in compliance with the accrual basis of accounting under IPSAS No. 1;
Direct the City Accountant to cease from granting additional cash advances unless those previously granted to an accountable officer is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made;
Demand immediate settlement or liquidation of cash advances and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel settlement of their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement has been made after issuance of three demand letters; and
Ensure that request for write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advances are in accordance with the guidelines and procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2016-005.

7.23	We recommended to the management the following:
Enjoin the City Accountant, in coordination with the City Treasurer, to evaluate the purpose and status of the dormant bank accounts and, if deemed no longer necessary, close these accounts and return the balances to their respective source agencies or original funding sources;
Require the City Accountant to strictly comply with COA Circular No. 96-011 on the preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) and, in cases where bank statements are not received regularly, proactively coordinate with the banks to obtain the required documents;
Expedite the signing of the bank confirmation requests to facilitate the timely receipt of bank confirmations; and
Instruct the City Accountant to make representation with the Philippine National Bank to obtain the earliest possible bank records and reconcile them with the accounting records; and if the accounts are found to be still existing, direct the City Treasurer to initiate their closure and transfer the balance to either the LBP or DBP accounts of the LGU.

9.23	We recommended that management:
9.23.1	Expedite the full implementation of the programs/projects/activities funded by the National Government in order not to delay further the benefits expected from these PPAs;
9.23.2	Make representation with the Source Agencies (SAs) seeking authority to utilize the unexpended balances of unfeasible projects to PPAs aligned with intended purpose, otherwise return the funds to them in accordance with the provisions of the MOA;
9.23.3	Return to the SAs any unused funds of the completed projects as prescribed under COA Circular No. 94-013; and
9.23.4	Designate personnel to monitor the receipts and disbursements of funds with specific percentage allocation requirements to ensure propriety and timely disposition of funds.

10.23	We recommended to the management the following:
10.23.1	Require the City Development Council to submit justification on why projects were funded despite not being included in the Local Development Investment Program (LDIP), and ensure that all projects to be funded under the 20% DF are included in the LDIP in accordance with Item 3.2.1 of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1;
10.23.2	Direct the City Planning and Development Coordinator and the City Budget Officer to ensure that lump-sum appropriations in the Annual Investment Program (AIP) are fully supported by specific and well-defined projects by year-end to guarantee that PPAs under the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation ready in compliance with Item 3.2.3 of the aforementioned JMC;
Instruct the implementing offices to expedite the preparation of project documents such as Program of Works (POWs), and strengthen procurement planning and scheduling to avoid implementation delays and ensure projects start and end within the budget year; and
Enjoin the City Planning and Development Coordinator and the City Budget Officer to monitor and regularly evaluate the utilization of continuing appropriations, particularly excess balances from completed projects, and reprogram idle funds to other priority development projects to maximize fund use and avoid missed opportunities for service delivery.

12.12	We recommended to the management the following:
Develop and maintain a comprehensive database that contains all essential information about the applicants and supports the validation of the prioritization process;
Consider enhancing the application form to include all the required information necessary to address the prioritization criteria outlined in the ordinance;
Ensure that all the supporting documents, such as application forms and endorsement letters are submitted to the audit team for evaluation; and
Ensure the timely release of the educational assistance in accordance with the timeline stipulated in the ordinance to boost the students’ morale and motivation.

13.11	We recommended that management:
Direct the Local School Board (LSB) to identify the names of intended beneficiaries who were not able to receive the tablets and submit a written justification for their non-receipt;
Require the LSB to ensure that enrolment and personnel data used for procurement planning are updated and gathered closer to implementation period and to consider the inventory balances to minimize the risk of excess and/or outdated inventory;
Instruct the LSB to ensure immediate distribution of the undistributed tablets to eligible beneficiaries to prevent potential wastage of government resources resulting from the devices becoming outdated;
Require the City Accountant and the General Services Officer to conduct a reconciliation between the distribution list and actual physical count of the unclaimed or undistributed tablets and make the necessary adjusting entries for any discrepancies identified; and
Consider establishing a feedback mechanism involving intended beneficiaries to provide insights for future procurement planning, ensuring that items to be procured align with the evolving needs of intended users.

14.22	We recommended to the management to:
14.22.1	Strictly pursue the establishment of a GAD Code by instructing the GFPS to assist the Local Sanggunian in the formulation of the said code;
14.22.2	Develop, maintain, and regularly update the City’s GAD Database with the required information specified in Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 in aid of effective gender-responsive planning, programming and policy information;
14.22.3	Maximize the utilization of GAD funds through implementation of GAD-related PPAs and ensure that these are properly monitored in order to ascertain that GAD goals and objectives were attained as planned;
14.22.4	Promptly inform the concerned DILG Office in writing of any changes to the DILG-endorsed GPB, such as realignment or reversion of GAD funds and/or implementation of additional PPAs, and ensure that an acknowledgment of receipt is obtained from said office; and
14.22.5	Ensure submission of the DILG-endorsed GPB to the COA Audit Team within five (5) working days upon receipt of the approved GPB and furnish a copy of the GAD AR within five (5) working days from the end of January of the preceding year.

Fast-track the approval of the Physical Inventory Plan effecting modification to include the specific assignments/duties of the Inventory Committee members, and submit to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;

Prioritize implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in the circular to establish balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;

Enforce to the Inventory Committee the conduct of annual physical count of PPE, preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and its submission on or before January 31 of the ensuing year; 

Constitute a Disposal Committee to ensure the speedy process of disposal of properties as prescribed; and

Instruct the City Accountant to prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards for each group of PPEs and record promptly the acquisition, description, custody, estimated useful life, depreciation, impairment loss, disposal and other information about the asset.

Expedite the full implementation of the programs/projects/activities funded by the National Government in order not to delay further the benefits expected from the implementation of these PPAs;

Make representation with the Source Agency (SA) seeking authority to utilize the unexpended balances of unfeasible projects to PPAs aligned with its intended purpose, otherwise return the fund to the SA in accordance with the provisions of the MOA;

Return to the SAs any unused funds of the completed projects as prescribed under COA Circular No. 94-013; and

Require the City Accountant to evaluate each account and to make adjusting entries, if necessary.

Submit justification on the low utilization of LDRRMF and irregular charging of disbursements to the fund, and also the non-implementation of prior year’s audit recommendations;

Optimize the utilization of its LDRRMF to lessen the socio-economic and environmental impacts of disasters in the community and disaster risks, including projected climate risks, and to enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities of the community;

Meticulously and judiciously prepare and incorporate in the LDRRMFIP the prior years’ unspent LDRRM funds in accordance with the national, regional and provincial framework;

Strictly adhere to the guidelines set forth under COA Circular No. 2012-002 and NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1, and refrain from charging against the LDRRMF those programs, projects and activities not pertaining to disaster-related activities or not in accordance with the primary purpose for which the fund was established; and

Ensure timely preparation and submission of the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to the audit team to allow timely audit and verification of reported fund utilization as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-002.

Submit explanation on why the aforementioned positions especially the vital ones still remained vacant and why had there been increases during the year that resorted to the LGU’s hiring of JOs and COS;

Submit HRMO’s plan of action on these vacant positions prioritizing on the vital and mandatory ones to comply with the provisions of the Local Government Code; and

Submit justification on the hiring of all COS workers. Also, instruct the City HRMO to furnish the Personal Data Sheets of the COS workers to the audit team for proper audit disposition.

Require the City Engineer to (i) conduct an investigation on all infrastructure projects with negative slippage and the causes thereof and submit to the Local Chief Executive the results of said investigation for appropriate action; and (ii) adopt the policy guidelines issued by DPWH in addressing negative slippage and strictly implement the same;

Direct the City Accountant to refrain from making any payment to contractors with negative slippage of more than 15 percent for on-going contracts and 10 percent for expired contracts and require the erring contractors to submit documentation of their work accomplishments, verified correct by the City Engineer, showing that the negative slippage was not due to their fault nor negligence;

Refer the result of the investigation of the City Engineer on the negative slippage to the City Legal Office for appropriate legal action; and henceforth, make sure that all infrastructure projects are implemented in accordance with the contracted time frame as stipulated in the contract agreements and that any negative slippage is addressed accordingly;

Evaluate the investigation report from the City Engineer’s Office and if warranted, initiate the termination of contracts pursuant to Section III.A.2, Annex “I” of the Revised IRR of RA 9184; and

Enjoin BAC to disqualify all subsequent bids of contractors at fault pursuant to Section 34.3 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

Enjoin the GFPS to prepare the GAD Agenda or identify priority gender issues to be addressed by the City during the three-year term of its leadership and ensure that the GAD Agenda shall be the basis for the annual formulation of PPAs to be included in the City’s GAD Plan and Budget;

Develop, maintain, and regularly update the City’s GAD Database with the required information specified in Annex B of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 in aid of effective gender-responsive planning, programming and policy information;

Maximize the utilization of GAD funds through implementation of GAD-related PPAs and ensure that these are properly monitored in order to ensure that GAD goals and objectives were attained as planned; and

Direct the City Accountant in coordination with the GFPS to strictly comply the assignment of separate Responsibility Center Codes or subsidiary ledger for GAD to account all GAD-related financial transactions.

Fast-track the submission of Liquidation Report to TESDA on those transactions that has already been paid by the City;

Expedite the payments of all valid obligations, and return all unexpended cash balances to TESDA Region 10 immediately; 

Require the City Accountant to draw JEV to reclassify any fund balance from ‘Due to LGUs’ to ‘Due to National Government Agencies’ to present fairly the financial statements;

